-- 1. Create a "Blank" Migration
-- Run this command in your terminal. It tells Prisma, "I'm about to make a change that isn't in the schema file":

-- Bash
-- npx prisma migrate dev --create-only --name add_settlement_trigger
-- 2. Edit the SQL File
-- Prisma will create a new folder in prisma/migrations with a migration.sql file inside. It will be empty. Open it and paste your PostgreSQL trigger code:

-- SQL
-- -- 1. Create the Function
-- CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION handle_new_order_payout()
-- RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
-- BEGIN
--     -- Logic: If order is completed, do something...
--     RETURN NEW;
-- END;
-- $$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- -- 2. Create the Trigger
-- CREATE TRIGGER on_order_completed
-- AFTER UPDATE OF "orderStatus" ON "Order"
-- FOR EACH ROW
-- WHEN (NEW."orderStatus" = 'Completed')
-- EXECUTE FUNCTION handle_new_order_payout();
-- 3. Apply the Migration
-- Now, tell Prisma to actually run that SQL against your database:

-- Bash
-- npx prisma migrate dev
-- Why this is better than pgAdmin:
-- Version Control: Your trigger code is now in your Git repository. If a teammate clones your project, they get the trigger automatically when they run migrations.

-- Safety: If you ever wipe your database and run npx prisma migrate dev, Prisma will recreate the tables and the triggers in the correct order.

-- Environment Sync: It ensures your Local, Staging, and Production databases all have the exact same logic.